🚀 Handler ka concept — SailPoint me:-
Handler = wo class ya code jo task ka real kaam perform karta hai.
TaskDefinition me sirf task ka blueprint/configuration hota hai (name, category, schedule, etc.)
Handler me logic hota hai ki task actually kya karega

💡 Important Points:-
Handler class hoti hai (Java class)
Ye implement karti hai SailPoint ka TaskHandler interface
Execution time pe executor handler ko call karta hai
Multiple tasks ek hi handler use kar sakte hain
Custom logic likhna ho → custom handler bana sakte ho

🏗 Handler ka kaam — Step by Step:-
Step	Kaam
1	Task start hota hai
2	Executor task ko pick karta hai
3	Executor handler class ka execute() method call karta hai
4	Handler logic perform karta hai (Aggregation, Provisioning, Certification etc.)
5	Handler result return karta hai
6	Task status update hota hai (Completed, Failed etc.)

()👉 Executor = task ko actually chalane wala thread/class/engine.
🔹 Executor:-
Ye Java class hota hai jo task execution ke liye engine ko batata hai kaunse code ko run karna hai.
Example: "sailpoint.api.TaskExecutor"
Kaun banata hai?
Usually developer banata hai custom executor class.
Default executors SailPoint provide karta hai for standard tasks.
Use kyun hota hai?
Task engine ko batane ke liye “Ye code run karna hai”.Reusable execution logic create karne ke liye.

🔹 2. Handler:-
Definition / Matlab
Handler bhi ek Java class hai, lekin ye task-specific logic handle karta hai.
Matlab:-
Executor task ko run karega, aur handler decide karega task ke andar kya kaam hoga.
Kaam / Responsibilities
Task ke business logic ko implement karta hai.
Input parameters process karta hai (e.g., identities, accounts).
Output / result prepare karta hai.
TaskDefinition me assign hota hai, taki jab task run ho handler ka code execute ho jaye.
Kaun banata hai?
Mostly developer, jab koi custom processing logic chahiye.
SailPoint ke paas standard handlers hote hain common tasks ke liye (Certification, Provisioning, Aggregation).
Use kyun hota hai?
Task ke andar jo real kaam hoga uske liye.
Executor sirf task start/stop karta hai, handler task ka kaam perform karta hai.

🔹 3. Executor vs Handler – Difference:-
Feature	              Executor	                                     Handler
Role:----------Task execution ko control karta hai:--------Task-specific logic perform karta hai
Example:-------sailpoint.api.TaskExecutor:-----------------sailpoint.task.certification.Handler
Banata:--------SailPoint ya developer (custom):---------------------Mostly developer
Focus;---------Task run karna, engine interaction:------------Business logic / processing
Assignment:----TaskDefinition me executor assign hota hai:----TaskDefinition me handler assign hota hai

💡 Example Flow:-
Task run hota hai → Executor trigger hota hai
Executor task context create karta hai
Executor Handler call karta hai
Handler business logic execute karta hai
Result Executor ke through task system me update hota hai

🔹 1. Executor:-
Type: Java Interface / Class
Purpose: Task ko run karne ke liye engine ko batata hai kaunsa code execute karna hai.
Default Example: sailpoint.api.TaskExecutor
Custom: Developer apni class bana sakta hai implements TaskExecutor karke.
Key Point: Ye task ko execute karne ka framework-level handle hai, logic nahi.

🔹 2. Handler:-
Type: Java Class
Purpose: Task ke andar ka specific business logic perform karta hai.
Default Example: sailpoint.task.certification.Handler
Custom: Developer apni class bana sakta hai extends Handler karke aur apna logic likh sakta hai.
Key Point: Ye task ka kaam perform karta hai, engine ko bas Executor ke through call kiya jata hai.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
()🔹 Executor:-
🔹 Executor (sailpoint.api.TaskExecutor):-
void execute(Task task, TaskResult result, SailPointContext context)
(Sirf 1 primary method in interface)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔹 Handler (sailpoint.task.Handler / sub‑classes):-
Note: Handler class ke methods based on SailPoint IdentityIQ core framework.

public void execute(TaskContext context)
public Map<String, Object> getResults()
public void init(Task task)
public void finish(TaskResult result)
public void setParameters(Map<String, Object> params)
public Map<String, Object> getParameters()

🔹 Certification Handler (sailpoint.task.certification.Handler):-
(inherits parent Handler methods; may include these)

public void review(AccessReview review)
public void performReviewActions()
public int getReviewCount()
public void setReviewCount(int count)

🔹 Aggregation Handler (sailpoint.task.AggregationHandler):-
public void process()
public void aggregateAccount(Account account)
public void aggregateIdentity(Identity identity)
public void processAttributes(Map<String,Object> attrs)

🔹 Provisioning Handler (sailpoint.task.ProvisioningHandler):-
public void provision(ProvisioningPlan plan)
public void processResults(ProvisioningResult result)
public List<ProvisioningPlan> getPlans()

🔹 Certification Reconciliation Handler:-
public void reconcile()
public void setReconciliationResults(List<Object> list)
public List<Object> getReconciliationResults()

🔹 Quick List (common handler methods):-
public void start()
public void stop()
public boolean isEnabled()
public void setEnabled(boolean status)
public void cleanup()
public void reset()
public void terminate()        // kabhi termination support ke liye
public boolean isFinished()    // status check

