()1️⃣ TaskResult aur SailPointContext ka source?
()SailPointContext:-
Ye SailPoint IdentityIQ engine ke through create hota hai.Engine ke andar developer ya admin context ke through tasks ko run karta hai.
()TaskResult:-
Ye bhi task execution ke time engine create karta hai aur executor ko pass karta hai,
jisse executor status set kar sake, messages add kar sake, validate kar sake.
()Task:-TaskDefinition se engine ke andar create hota hai aur run time pe executor ko milta hai.
Matlab: tu manually new TaskResult() ya new SailPointContext() create nahi karega. Ye sab engine handle karta hai.

1️⃣ TaskDefinition aur Task ka creation responsibility:-
Object	               Kaun Create Karta Hai	                                             Notes
()TaskDefinition------------------Admin--------------------IdentityIQ me Admin UI se ya XML import / console se create karta hai. Ye define karta hai:
                                                       • Task ka name
                                                       • Executor class (jo developer ne banaya)
                                                       • Schedule, category, description, tags etc.

()Task--------------------SailPoint Engine---------------Jab scheduled ya manually run hota hai,
                                                       tab engine TaskDefinition se Task instance create karta hai aur executor ko pass karta hai.
                                                       Developer manually Task create nahi karta, wo sirf executor me logic likhta hai.
													 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1️⃣ Admin: TaskDefinition Creation (Java-style, normally IdentityIQ admin UI me hota hai)
package com.example.sailpoint.admin;

import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.object.TaskDefinition;

public class TaskDefinitionAdmin {

    public static TaskDefinition createTaskDefinition(SailPointContext context) throws Exception {
        // New TaskDefinition create karna
        TaskDefinition taskDef = new TaskDefinition();
        taskDef.setName("DemoTask");
        taskDef.setDescription("This is a demo task created by admin.");
        taskDef.setExecutorClass("com.example.sailpoint.tasks.DeveloperTaskExecutor"); // developer executor
        taskDef.setCategory("Demo");
        taskDef.setTemplate(false);

        // Context me save karna
        context.saveObject(taskDef);
        context.commitTransaction();

        System.out.println("TaskDefinition created: " + taskDef.getName());
        return taskDef;
    }
}
2️⃣ Engine: Task & TaskResult Generation (Normally handled by IdentityIQ engine)
package com.example.sailpoint.engine;

import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.object.Task;
import sailpoint.task.TaskResult;
import sailpoint.object.TaskDefinition;

public class TaskEngineSimulator {

    public static void runTask(SailPointContext context, TaskDefinition taskDef) {
        try {
            // Engine creates Task instance
            Task task = new Task();
            task.setName(taskDef.getName());
            task.setId("T12345"); // Normally engine generates unique ID
            System.out.println("Task instance created: " + task.getName());

            // Engine creates TaskResult
            TaskResult result = new TaskResult();
            result.setStatus(TaskResult.Status.Ready);

            // Developer executor call
            com.example.sailpoint.tasks.DeveloperTaskExecutor executor = new com.example.sailpoint.tasks.DeveloperTaskExecutor();
            executor.execute(task, result, context);

            // After execution, engine would commit result
            context.saveObject(result);
            context.commitTransaction();

            System.out.println("Task execution finished. Status: " + result.getStatus());

        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
3️⃣ Developer: Executor (Logic/Handler)
package com.example.sailpoint.tasks;

import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.task.Task;
import sailpoint.task.TaskExecutor;
import sailpoint.task.TaskResult;

/**
 * Developer writes task execution logic here
 */
public class DeveloperTaskExecutor implements TaskExecutor {

    @Override
    public void execute(Task task, TaskResult result, SailPointContext context) {
        try {
            System.out.println("Executing task: " + task.getName());
            result.setStatus(TaskResult.Status.Running);
            result.addMessage("DeveloperTaskExecutor started execution.");

            // =========================================
            // Handler-like logic inside executor
            // =========================================
            defaultHandler(task, result, context);

            // Complete TaskResult
            result.setCompletionStatus(TaskResult.Status.Completed);
            result.addMessage("DeveloperTaskExecutor finished execution.");

        } catch (Exception e) {
            result.setStatus(TaskResult.Status.Failure);
            result.addMessage("Task execution failed: " + e.getMessage());
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    // Handler method simulating internal logic
    private void defaultHandler(Task task, TaskResult result, SailPointContext context) {
        System.out.println("Handler running for task: " + task.getName());
        // Simple demo logic
        result.addMessage("Handler logic executed successfully.");
    }
}
4️⃣ Full Flow: Notepad Test
package com.example.sailpoint.main;

import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import com.example.sailpoint.admin.TaskDefinitionAdmin;
import com.example.sailpoint.engine.TaskEngineSimulator;
import sailpoint.object.TaskDefinition;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        SailPointContext context = null;

        try {
            // 🔹 Normally engine provides context
            context = SailPointFactory.createContext();

            // 1️⃣ Admin creates TaskDefinition
            TaskDefinition taskDef = TaskDefinitionAdmin.createTaskDefinition(context);

            // 2️⃣ Engine runs Task & TaskResult
            TaskEngineSimulator.runTask(context, taskDef);

        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        } finally {
            if (context != null) {
                context.decache(true);
                context.close();
            }
        }
    }
}
///////////*
2️⃣ TaskEngineSimulator.runTask(context, taskDef);
Ye line Notepad/testing purpose ke liye maine banayi thi, real production me SailPoint engine automatically ye karta hai:-
TaskEngineSimulator.runTask(context, taskDef);
🔹 Ye kya karti hai:-
TaskDefinition se Task instance create karna,
Engine normally task ka unique instance generate karta hai.
Example: task.setName(taskDef.getName())

()TaskResult create karna:-
Engine runtime pe result object banata hai
Example: TaskResult result = new TaskResult();

()Developer executor ko call karna:-
Example: executor.execute(task, result, context);
Yaha defaultHandler() bhi call hota hai

()TaskResult save & commit karna:-
Engine me ye commit hota hai database me

🔹 Kaun call karta hai:-
Notepad test me → hum manually call karte hain
Production me → SailPoint server engine automatically call karta hai

🔹 Effect:-
Task instance aur TaskResult generate hota hai
Executor ka execute() method run hota hai
Internal handler logic execute hota hai
TaskResult ka final status engine me commit hota hai


1️⃣ defaultHandler(task, result, context); ka purpose:-
Ye executor ke andar ek method call hai, jo developer ka internal “handler” logic run karne ke liye hota hai.

🔹 Kya hum isme karte hain?
Yes bhai, ye wahi jagah hai jahan developer apna task logic likhta hai.
Example ke liye:-
User provisioning
Approval checks
Logging messages
Any other business logic
Ye handler method modular banata hai:agar executor ka logic bada hai, to ye step-wise divide ho jata hai.
*///////////
