()taskDef.setExecutorClass("sailpoint.task.AccountAggregationExecutor"); ye kya karta hai taskdefinition me?
--💥 Ye karta kya hai?

👉 Ye TaskDefinition ko bind karta hai ek built-in SailPoint executor se
Matlab:-
"Jab ye task run hoga → Account Aggregation logic chalega"
👉 AccountAggregationExecutor = SailPoint ka ready-made engine logic
✔ Accounts fetch karega
✔ Application se data laayega
✔ Identity se match karega
✔ Update karega system me

🔽 Step-by-step:-
1️⃣ Task run hota hai (UI / Scheduler se)
2️⃣ Engine TaskDefinition load karta hai
3️⃣ executorClass read karta hai
4️⃣ AccountAggregationExecutor load hota hai
5️⃣ execute() call hota hai
-------------------------------------------------
🔥 Inside AccountAggregationExecutor:-


(1)🔥 ✅ SABSE SHURU ME KYA HOTA HAI?
🧠 1️⃣ TaskDefinition CREATE hota hai (CONFIG STAGE)

👉 Sabse pehle system me ye hota hai:-
TaskDefinition taskDef = new TaskDefinition();

taskDef.setName("MyTask");
taskDef.setExecutorClass("sailpoint.task.AccountAggregationExecutor");

👉 Matlab:-
"Ye task jab chalega → AccountAggregationExecutor chalega"
fir Enfine call karega executor.execute(task, result, context);


🧠 Example se samajh:-
--taskDef.setExecutorClass("com.example.sailpoint.tasks.DeveloperTaskExecutor");
--fir ye Engine call karta hai:-
executor.execute(task, result, context);
()executor = us class ka object hai jo tu setExecutorClass() me deta hai,jaise:-
------------
